  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law and national laws on money laundering intersect in several important ways:\n\n1. International Standards and Agreements\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- Multilateral agreements setting global anti-money laundering (AML) standards\n\n2. Legal Cooperation Mechanisms\n- Mutual legal assistance treaties\n- Information sharing between financial intelligence units\n- Extradition agreements\n- Cross-border investigation collaboration\n\n3. Compliance Requirements\n- Banks and financial institutions must implement international AML standards\n- Reporting suspicious transactions\n- Customer due diligence procedures\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n\n4. Regulatory Harmonization\n- Countries adapting national laws to match international frameworks\n- Consistent definitions of money laundering\n- Standardized reporting and investigation protocols\n\n5. Enforcement Mechanisms\n- International sanctions\n- Asset freezing and seizure\n- Coordinated legal actions against transnational financial crimes\n\n6. Technology and Information Exchange\n- Shared digital platforms for tracking financial transactions\n- Global databases of suspicious activities\n- Advanced technological tools for detecting money laundering patterns\n\nThese intersections create a complex, multilayered approach to combating financial crimes globally.",
